    <item>
      <title>Less sun, more back pain (low vitamin D)</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/less-sun-more-back-pain-low-vitamin-d/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 29 Jun 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/less-sun-more-back-pain-low-vitamin-d/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h4 id=&#34;low-back-pain-lack-of-sun-by-marc-sorenson-eddhttpsunlightinstituteorglow-back-pain-sun-exposure&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://sunlightinstitute.org/low-back-pain-sun-exposure/&#34;&gt;LOW-BACK PAIN: LACK OF SUN? BY MARC SORENSON, EDD&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;“First of all, low-back pain is pandemic in much of the world. And, it is especially common in countries where most women wear clothing that prevents sun exposure to the skin.&lt;a href=&#34;DOI:%2010.1007/s10067-007-0603-4&#34;&gt;DOI: 10.1007/s10067-007-0603-4&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;“One of the first studies to show an association between LBP and reduced sun exposure was done in England: ] Northerners were 3-4 times as likely to suffer low-back pain as southerners. Of course, we know that there is less sunshine in the north.”&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
